it is a good game. don't confuse what I'm about to say. the game doesn't fit any mold of the term rogue that I'm aware of. you level up through steady progression, collect loot, and play through set missions and maps. there's no randomized playthroughs, no resetting of certain aspects of progression, no loss of loot, and no randomized dungeons. it's a straight forward turn based game. it's good, but you should purchase the game with this understanding in mind.

And the scantily-clad female NPCs with gravity-defying, constantly-bouncing breasts make it hard to see this as a game that wants to be taken seriously. Such a shame, Nine Tails.

After playing for sometime I've begun to dislike the playstyle. Combat is 
fun and requires some strategy but the puzzles later in the game will annoy 
you. Had I known some parts of the main quest line were unbeatable withing 
solving a puzzle I would not have purchased the game. Later on the puzzles 
are unforgiving so one wrong move you start over. This wouldn't be so bad 
if the controls weren't so clunky. Here's a game with a grid based movement 
system but not grid based controls. This often leads to your character 
misstepping or swinging by accident wasting a turn or turning what should 
have been one turn into 3 to make up for the mistake. Since the latter 
puzzles allow for practically no mistakes this becomes extremely 
frustrating. I don't even like puzzles. To the developers: consider adding 
the option for a static game pad, like what snes had (8 directional) just 
like your grids. This would allow for much fewer mistakes. Also consider 
players to either skip the puzzle if they die to it or don't charge for 
repeated deaths to puzzles. Fail a few times and you're either retreating 
and doing the entire level over again or you're broke and end up repeating 
older levels to make cash to try again. Most players don't like that level 
of repetition. I unfortunately have given up on the game due to the 
repetitive playstyle.

Love the whole idea of the game, however control and difficulty in gaining 
equipments as well as gems should be made easier. Also some magic skills 
would be nice though I'm not sure it is possible. Would love to have 2 
characters roaming the dungeons together too.

bad and spoil my mood.

I *want* to like this one. The movement and combat scheme really does seem 
like 21st century version of the classic Rogue. Boss fights are challenging 
and require chess-like strategy. Artwork is very professional, with one 
exception: does EVERY female have to be dressed like a stripper with a 
heaving bosom? (Classy.) Music is decent. Unfortunately, side quests become 
monotonous, and so does the tedious "story." Either put some real thought 
into it, or don't make us click though boring, pointless cutscenes. The 
choice to limit play to only one character at a time makes grinding take 
twice as long. The worst part is the gear-crafting and upgrading process; 
it's a time-consuming and unnecessarily tedious chore. Nobody wants an 
actual "time-waster." It's too bad. If Ninetail just dropped the 
superfluous story and didn't try to cram in a stick-gathering "survival" 
element, it would actually be a better game.

Beautful looking game and satisfying  controls/combat. It's fast paced, and so far, the story is mildy entertaining. Sadly I feel little mislead. I bought the game expecting a rogue-lite, but what I got was a fast paced action game that requires very little thought or foresight. The game is very easy, and if you die, you can "try again", starting you at the doorway of the room you died in. There is also a premium currency to get "extra special crates" after some bosses, which is annoying since it's not a free game. All in all good game, but not what I was expecting or looking for.

Criticism first, then praise.  I do not like seeing IAP in a game that I bought.  Plain and simple.  Dislike that I'm dungeon crawling, defeat a group of enemies, get an awesome chest, then am asked to use special (purchase now!) coins to open the chest.  Really a break from immersion and I hate it, minus one star.  That said, I knew from the first screenshot that I was going to buy this game.  I love the gameplay and the artstyle is great.  I like how your character changes appearance based on equipped items.  I like crawling and replaying levels to get better loot.  Little hard on my battery, but that just means I have to plug into the wall every once in a while to recharge.  Love almost every aspect of the game (get rid of IAP, please).
Overall it had been amazing so far!

Roguelike is a very specific thing, this was not even roguelite, let alone roguelike. First off they need to be hard, have permadeath, random levels and loot and encourage replayability, I dont know if it has perna death as the first two levels never saw me droping even a point of heath, but given the railroaded story line and the division of missions Im guessing not. Additionally there were hints of tipical ftp grind fests all over, which doesnt boad well for long term play. Bottom line if you want a roguelike play something esle.
